Interference to spouse employment describes a situation where your spouse or partner is experiencing some kind of interruption to their employment or job.
Disruption to children's education describes a situation where a dependent under your care is experiencing some kind of disturbance or problem that interrupts their schooling.
Family separation describes a situation where you are being posted to a job that is not in the same location as your family.
Dislocation from extended family describes a situation where you, your family or extended family are separated from each other, or desirable services like familiar doctors.
Family with special needs describes a situation where someone in your family requires additional support for medical or educational reasons.

Your own medical needs describes a situation where you are looking to be granted, deferred, cancelled or screened from an attachment, deployment or posting because of a personal medical condition or situation.

Disadvantage in home ownership describes a situation where your absence because of a Service attachment, deployment or posting may contribute towards an undesirable outcome for any real estate that you own, rent or manage.
Desire to collocate with a spouse or partner describes a situation where you are looking to be posted in the location where your partner is currently residing or situated.
“Family separation” and “Dislocation from extended family” are both situations where distance from family is an issue.
When you are posted to a job that’s not in the same location as your family, any issues arising from that is considered “family separation.”
When the location of your family disrupts their ability to be with other family members or desirable services, any issues arising from that is considered “dislocation from extended family.”

A Compassionate Posting is when a member is granted, deferred, cancelled or screened from an attachment, deployment or posting. If an application for a Compassionate Posting is approved the member is held in a nominated location for an approved duration. (They are capped to 24 months.)

It may be granted in situations where a member is experiencing the death or life-threatening illness or injury of a close relative, urgent personal circumstances, or serious problems in domestic or financial affairs at home when their presence would improve the situation.
